        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was twenty cubits square (long and broad) and ten cubits high, and constructed on the model of the Mosaic altar of burnt-offering, and probably of brass plates, which enclosed the inner core, consisting of earth and unhewn stones; and if we may judge from Ezekiel's description, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 43:13-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it rose in steps, as it were, so that at each step its extent was smaller; and the measurement of twenty cubits refers only to the lowest scale, while the space at the top, with the hearth, was only twelve cubits square; cf. my Bibl. Archaeol. i. S. 127, with the figure, plate iii. fig. 2.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
